column5: DOHCとは　2ほんのカムシャフトが　それぞれ　はいきときゅうきの　バルブをくどうする　ほうしきである。
column6: [i]DOHC[std] refers to a configuration with two camshafts: one driving the exhaust valves and the other the intake valves.
column10: "A dual overhead cam, double overhead cam, or twin-cam engine has two camshafts over each bank of the cylinder head,[1][2] one for the intake valves and another for the exhaust valves. Therefore there are two camshafts for a straight engine and a total of four camshafts for a V engine or a flat engine." — Supper (2025-04-18 12:45:15)

column5: CPUチューンを　してないクルマは　180Kmでリミッターがはたらくため　それいじょうの　スピードは　でないようになっている。
column6: Cars without CPU tuning have a limiter in effect that prevents them from reaching speeds above 180 km/h.

column5: クルマのぜんりんと　こうりんのしゃじくのきょりをホイールベースという。
column6: The distance between the axles of a car's front and rear wheels is called its [i]wheelbase[std].
column10: "In both road and rail vehicles, the wheelbase is the horizontal distance between the centers of the front and rear wheels." — Supper (2025-04-18 12:48:27)

column5:
みぎタイヤとひだりタイヤのあいだの　ながさをトレッドという。\n
ぜんごでは　ながさが　ちがうのがふつうです。
column6: The length of the gap between the left and right tires is called the [i]tread[std]. Normally, this differs between the front and the rear.

column5: ブレーキには　ディスクブレーキとドラムブレーキがあり　さいきんは　こうせいのうな　ディスクブレーキを　もつクルマが　おおくなってきた。
column6: Brakes may be [i]disc brakes[std] or [i]drum brakes[std], and lately, many cars have begun to be equipped with high-performance disc brakes.

column5: きゅうき、あっしゅく、ばくはつ、はいき　という　4つのこうていを　くりかえすエンジンを4サイクルエンジンという。げんざいのクルマのほとんどがこのほうしきである。
column6: An engine that repeats the four stages of intake, compression, combustion, and exhaust is a [i]four-cycle engine[std]. Nearly all modern cars use one.

column5: ピストンの　ちょっけいにあたるぶぶんのながさを　ボアといい　ピストンのうごくきょりをストロークという。
column6: The width of the region that corresponds to the diameter of a piston is called the [i]bore[std], and the distance a piston moves is called its [i]stroke[std].
column10:
"In a piston engine, the bore (or cylinder bore) is the diameter of each cylinder."
"In the context of an internal combustion engine, the term stroke has the following related meanings: ... "Stroke length", the distance travelled by the piston during each cycle. The stroke length, along with bore diameter, determines the engine's displacement." — Supper (2025-04-18 12:56:42)

column5: エンジンのパワーをたんたいでそくていしたものをグロスといいクルマにのせたじょうたいでそくていしたものをネットという。げんざいのクルマのパワーはネットでけいさんされる。
column6: An engine's power measured by itself is called the [i]gross[std], and as attached to a car is called the [i]net[std]. Modern cars' power is computed as net.

column5: クルマが　まがるときには　うちがわのタイヤと　そとがわのタイヤに　かいてんさがしょうじる。それを　ほせいするのがデフギアである。
column6: When turning, a difference in revolutions occurs between a car's inner and outer wheels. What compensates for that is a [i]differential gear[std].
column10: "A differential is a gear train with three drive shafts that has the property that the rotational speed of one shaft is the average of the speeds of the others. A common use of differentials is in motor vehicles, to allow the wheels at each end of a drive axle to rotate at different speeds while cornering." — Supper (2025-04-18 13:08:24)

column5: エンジンが　うんてんせきのまえにあり　こうりんをくどうするのを　FRという。むかしからあるので　ぎじゅつてきにもかんせいされており　うんてんするたのしみも　おおきい。
column6: Having an engine in front of the driver's seat that drives the rear wheels is called [i]FR[std]. An old design, it's highly developed and very fun to drive.

column5:
エンジンが　うんてんせきのまえにあり　ぜんりんをくどうするほうしきを　FFという。\n
プロペラシャフトを　もたないので　しつないをひろくできる
column6: Putting an engine that drives the front wheels in front of the driver's seat is called [i]FF[std]. The lack of a propeller shaft means the interior can be larger.

column5:
エンジンが　うんてんせきのすぐうしろにあるものを　MRという。\n
よくスポーツカーにつかわれるが　しつないがせまい。
column6: Putting the engine directly behind the driver's seat is called [i]MR[std]. Many sports cars do this, but it results in a cramped interior.

column5: タイヤを　4りんともうごかすほうしきを　4WDという。すべりやすいろめんで　しんかをはっきするが　さいきんでは　モータースポーツでも　おおくみられるようになってきた。
column6: A setup that drives all four wheels is called [i]4WD[std]. It's most useful on slippery roads, but lately, it's grown common in motorsports too.

column5:
クルマのデザインには　りゅうこうがあり　まるいクルマと　かくばったクルマが　こうごにはやるといわれる。\n
ちなみに　いまは　まるいクルマがはやっている。
column6: Cars have design trends, and they say hot designs alternate between rounded and square. Incidentally, rounded cars are currently popular.

column5: きりもなければ　あめもふっていないひに　フォグランプを　つけてはしっているクルマが　おおくみられる。ひとのめいわくだし　とてもはずかしいのでみんなでわらってやろう！
column6: Cars are often seen with fog lights on even during dry spells. It's a bother, and also really embarrassing, so let's all laugh at them!

column5: じゅうたいのげんいんは　ほとんどが　こうさてんふきんのいほうちゅうしゃにあるという。ろじょうちゅうしゃは　やめよう！
column6: It's said that almost all traffic congestion results from illegal parking near intersections. Quit parking on the street!

column5:

column6: A rear spoiler uses air force to press the car downward. Under maximal conditions, F1 cars generate over a ton of force.

column5: ながいくだりざかで　ブレーキをずっとつかっていると　とつぜん　ブレーキがきかなくなることがあるので　うまくエンジンブレーキを　つかいながら　はしるようにしよう。
column6: Using the brakes for a long time while going down a big hill can cause them to suddenly give out, so use the engine brake effectively when driving.

column10: "speeds" or "gears"? they're both "soku" in Japanese. and "chuuteisoku" doesn't seem to be a "real word" -- is it "medium and low", or "medium-low"? — Supper (2025-04-21 18:27:21)

column6: This is an exhaust manifold.\n

column5: エンジンとマフラーの　あいだにとりつけてはいきかんしょうを　なくすものだ
column6:
[clear]
It attaches between the engine and muffler to reduce exhaust interference.
column10: 排気干渉 [url]https://www.jsme.or.jp/jsme-medwiki/doku.php?id=11:1009970[/url] — Supper (2025-04-13 11:43:55)

column6: This is a limited-slip differential (LSD).
column10: [url]https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Limited-slip_differential[/url] — Supper (2025-04-13 11:47:03)

column5:
ローギアに　せっていしてあるから\n
かそくが　よくなるぞ
column6:
[clear]
It's set to a low gear, so it'll improve your acceleration.

column5: これはインタークーラーだ\n
column6: This is an intercooler.\n

column5:
ターボや　スーパーチャージャーなどのかきゅうき　つきのエンジンにはぜひ\n
ほしいパーツだ
column6: If you've got a turbo or supercharger on your engine, you'll definitely want this.

column5:
コンピューターを　かいりょうして\n
リミッターを　はずす
column6: This modifies the computer to remove the limiter.

column5:
きゅうはいきの　とおりみちを\n
なめらかにして\n
ていこうを　へらす
column6: This smooths out the passage of intake and exhaust, decreasing resistance.

column5:
あっしゅくひを　あげて　より　きょうりょくな　ばくはつりょくをえる\n
こうかいてんで　パワーアップじゃ
column6: This raises the compression ratio and increases combustion power, upping power at high RPMs.

column5:
シリンダーを　おおきくして\n
エンジンの　はいきりょうを　ふやす
column6: This enlarges the cylinders, increasing engine displacement.

column5:
しゃたいを　かるくする\n
ゼロヨンには　ふかけつじゃ
column6: This lightens the car body. It's a must for zero yon.

column5: がんばって　こいよ！！
column6: Keep at it, boy!

おお　\p\n
きょうは　なんのようじゃ？
column6:
Oh, \p.\n
What'll it be today?

column5:
じつは　こんどの　日本一けっていせんで\n
メカニックが　ひつようなんだ\n
ガンさん　やってくれるでしょ
column6:
Actually, I need to have a mechanic for the Japanese championship race.\n
You'll do it for me, right?

column5:
わしは　ゼロヨンは　きらいじゃ\n
ほかに　たのめ！
column6:
I despise zero yon.\n
Ask somebody else!

column5: そんな　せっしょうな
column6: What? So cruel...

column5:
いやじゃといったら　いやじゃ！！\n
しごとの　じゃまするなら　はよ　かえれ！
column6: I said I won't do it, and that's [b]final![std] Now if you're just going to get in the way, you can make like a tree!

column5:
なんだよ　けちー！\n
ガンコの　ガンさんとは　よくいったもんだ
column6:
Christ, what a grouch!\n
No wonder they call him Grumpy Gan.

column5:
べつに　ガンコだから　ガンさんって\n
いうわけじゃ　ないぜ
column6: It might alliterate nicely, but did you know that {Gan} isn't actually his real name?
column10: we're now literally explaining the derivation of his name as a way to introduce the plot element that he's related to King, which is of course all untranslatable, so we'll just have to make something up here. I suppose I could have taken the tack of giving him a different, more localization-friendly nickname, but changing characters' terms of address doesn't sit well with me if they're not inherently meaningful words like "old man" or what have you. — Supper (2025-04-17 14:42:28)

column6: Oh, really?

column5:
ガンさんの　みょうじは　岩本っていうんだ\n
その　岩のじをとって　ガンさんってわけさ
column6: His last name is Iwamoto. The character for {iwa} can be pronounced {gan,} which is where that comes from.

column5:
岩本っていったら　ゼロヨンキングと\n
おなじ　みょうじじゃないか\n
もしかして　しんせきとか？
column6:
Iwamoto? Wait, isn't that the same last name as the Zero Yon King?\n
Are they related?
Father and son.

column5: おやこ？　キングとガンさんが？
column6: Father and son? King and [i]Gan?[std]

column5: ああ　むかしは　なかがよかったんだが・・・おっと　いけね！
column6: Yeah. Once upon a time, they got along, but—Whoops, never mind!

column5: なんじゃ　まだ　おったのか
column6: What, you're still here?

column5: キングと　ガンさんが　おやこって　ほんと？
column6: Is it true that King's your son?

column5:
あいつめ　よけいなことを　いいおって\n
ああ　ほんとうじゃ\n
あいつは　わしの　ひとりむすこじゃ
column6: That rat's been running his mouth, has he? Yes, it's true. He's my only son.

column5:
やつは　ゼロヨンを　やるといって\n
いえを　とびだしていった\n
わしら　ふうふを　おきざりにして
column6: He ran out of the house blathering about racing zero yon, deserting his parents.

column5: やつの　ははおやは　そのよくとしにしんだ\n
column6: His mother died the year after.\n

column5:
しぬまぎわまで　やつのことを\n
しんぱいしておった
column6: She worried for him till the moment she was gone.

column5:
わしは　そんなみがってな\n
あいつを　ゆるさん！！
column6: I'll never forgive that selfish, egotistical boy!

column5:
そんなことが　あったのか・・・\n
ごめんよ　　よりによって　キングとの\n
レースに　ガンさんを　つれていこうなんて
column6:
Wow, I had no idea...\n
Sorry, I wouldn't have asked [i]you[std] of all people to come to a race against King.

column5:
いや　いいんじゃ\n
それに　かんがえが　かわった
column6:
No, it's fine.\n
I've changed my mind anyways.

column5:
つぎのレース　わしが\n
メカニック　としていってやろう\n
おまえの　クルマを
column6: I'll be your car's mechanic for the next race.

column5:
とびっきり　はやくして　あいつを\n
日本一から\n
ひきずりおろしてやる！
column6: I'll make it so fast, it'll knock him off his high horse as the best in Japan!

column5:
だからおまえも\n
せいいっぱい　うんてんしろ
column6: So, you'd better drive like hell, boy!

column5:
うん　オレやるよ！\n
ぜったいキングに　かってみせる
column6:
You got it!\n
I'll beat King or die trying.

column5:
そうか　でも　やつの　クルマは　はやいぞ\n
じゅうぶんに　チューンしておけ
column6:
All right. His car's fast, though.\n
Make sure you tune everything up as far as it'll go.

12かいばらいで　よいでしょうか　？
column6: with monthly payments of ¥[num5ff]<$B8><$20>,000 for 12 months. Is that all right?

column10:
context? there's a decent chance we don't need this string at all, since the yen sign should go on the front of the number and linebreaks are dynamically computed. — Supper (2025-04-17 16:19:10)
it looks like this happens if you have a down payment of 0 yen? surely that's not actually possible? ...or actually, unless I'm missing something here, apparently this happens anytime the low byte of your down payment amount is 0, which seems like a bug (means that a down payment of 256,000 will be displayed as 256, 512,000 will be 512, etc.). not going to bother fixing this since I'm not sure the game will ever even generate such amounts, but it's worth noting.
anyway, we should clear this out, since the linebreak will just mess up the flow. — Supper (2025-04-30 17:14:44)

やっぱり　あきらめます

きんりもやすいし　なにかと　おとくですよ

column5:
うーん　かってもいいけど\n
ちょっとたかいなあ・・・
column6: Hmm. Well, I'd like to buy it, but that's kinda high...

column5:
もうちょっと　やすくしてくれたら\n
すぐかっちゃうんだけどなあ・・・
column6: I'd be all over it if it were just a bit cheaper.
Mmm-hmm...

column5: すこしくらい　まけてくれるんでしょ
column6: You can give me a little discount, right?

column5:

なんとかなりますけど
column6: Perhaps, if it's only a little bit.
All right then.

column5: それは　ちょっとむりですね
column6: I'm afraid you're asking for too much.

column5:

おねがいします

おとどけします

いたしましょうか？

ぶんかつばらいも　むりですね

column5:
テクマクマザコンおとこは、\n
なさけない！
column6: Super-cali-fragi-listEXPLOSION!!
column10:
parodying the magic words uttered by the titular protagonist of the magical girl series Himitsu no Akko-chan when she uses her magic mirror to transform into somebody: 「テクマクマヤコン テクマクマヤコン　○○になれ～」 (thanks Pixipedia). here, マヤコン is twisted to マザコン. I guess it really shouldn't surprise me that there's a "~con" term for mothers, though the dictionary claims it also can just mean "a mama's boy".
TODO: localize? is that even possible short of making something completely different up? — Supper (2025-04-11 06:38:31)

column5:

column6: Yabba-dabba-DOOOOOOMSDAY!!
column10:
derived from the opening lyrics to the Mahou Tsukai Sally theme ([url]https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=jk5vDJYIXlM[/url]), which I'm pretty sure are meant to be "magic-like" mumbo-jumbo: マハリクマハリタ　ヤンバラヤンヤンヤン
(the last part is twisted to ヤンバルクイナ, the name of a bird species: [url]https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Okinawa_rail[/url])
TODO: do we want to try to localize or replace this? — Supper (2025-04-11 06:27:47)

column6: Summoning Bell
column10:
most likely a parody of the まよけのすず (Warding Bell, apparently "Banishing Bell" in the current official localization) from the Dragon Quest series, which has effects such as causing enemies to target you less frequently: [url]https://wikiwiki.jp/dqdic3rd/%E3%80%90%E3%81%BE%E3%82%88%E3%81%91%E3%81%AE%E3%81%99%E3%81%9A%E3%80%91[/url]
the effect of [i]this[/i] item, conversely, is to increase your chance of encountering thieves in the security guard minigame. the name is presumably invoking 寄す, which apparently means either "to welcome (into a group)" (in Kansai-ben) or "to bring near" (archaically), either of which describes its effect reasonably well. — Supper (2025-04-13 15:24:13)

column6: Car Stereo
4-Into-1 Muffler
column10: 手曲げマフラー is the Japanese name for what is apparently known in English as a "4-into-1 muffler" (the Japanese name is apparently derived from its shape, which resembles a bent hand: [url]https://delkevic.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/product13374_1b.jpg[/url]) — Supper (2025-04-13 15:29:48)

column6: Lucky Tires
Nitro Jet
column10:
the only stackable item, I believe (the game specially lists the quantity of them that you have on the item menu). these can be triggered by pressing Select during races, which gives you a speed boost. — Supper (2025-04-13 15:48:02)
NOTE: length of this item's name affects the placement of the quantity indicator (maintext-0x3B4_0)! if you change the length of that, you'll need to adjust this to match. — Supper (2025-04-22 14:34:12)

column10: TODO: the joke is that in Japanese, "aluminum wheel" (アルミホイール) is almost a homophone of "aluminum foil" (アルミホイル), causing the protagonist to accidentally buy the latter via mail order. this doesn't really work in English, so we'll have to try to work something out. somewhat tempted to make this a gag on "aluminum" vs. "aluminium" somehow. — Supper (2025-04-13 15:34:06)

column10:
お釜 おかま "effeminate gay man; male transvestite; (preoperative) transgender woman; (gay) male prostitute Usually written using kana alone, sensitive, colloquial Usu. オカマ; oft. derog."

"Okama" seems to occupy a strange niche where it's not "acceptable" for standard use, but also doesn't have the inherently offensive connotations of the less nice words you'll find used to translate it in other dictionaries:
[url]https://allabout-japan.com/en/article/5102/[/url]
'Popular media, including anime and manga, used the term for outlandish and effete characters. One example is the One Piece character Bentham, better known as Mr. 2 Bon Kurei (seen above is the cover for his song "オカマーチ" or "Okama March"). ... While both terms can be heard in private conversation, [i]okama[/i] and [i]onee[/i] are not acceptable terms to use in public.'
If this term was sufficiently acceptable to be used on One Piece, and it's not being used to actively denigrate anyone, it's probably not so strong in this context as to warrant the use of outright vulgarities in translation. But boy, this sure gave me pause for a loooong time. — Supper (2025-04-17 13:03:35)

column10:
good god, it's one of those lines where the whole translation suddenly grinds to a halt for 20 minutes as I frantically Google a bunch of shit that apparently every Japanese person knows so well that no one's ever bothered to write down the meaning of it.

チンチラばり refers to fuzzy vehicle upholstery, and judging by the neon colors in the photos I'm seeing, I assuming it's not literally made of chinchilla fur.

グラデコ seems to be an uncommon abbreviation for "gradation decoration". I'm honestly not sure if it's intended to refer to the paint job or some sort of decals, but frankly I've spent enough time trying to figure this out that I'm not inclined to care.

oh, and even レースのカーテン managed to trip me up for a minute because of course in a game like this, you're expecting "race", not "lace". whew.
— Supper (2025-04-17 10:03:16)

column10:
FIXME: our local encoding is not QUITE ascii-compliant, so there are probably some issues here. lower case letters are not mapped to the normal range, some punctuation symbols have been swapped around to different slots for obscure reasons related to the lip flap animations, and some codepoints are also filled with game-specific custom characters. but most save file names are nothing more than capital letters and numbers, and there's a good chance no one will even see this menu in the first place since the game only requires 0x28 bytes to save, so I'm willing to call it a day on this. — Supper (2025-04-21 10:53:24)
okay fiiiiine, I added a full ASCII font just for this. I'm sure someone will be grateful for it someday!! — Supper (2025-04-21 13:20:54)

column10: has no [wait] command in the original, so it disappears immediately after printing. apparently, I'm doing more testing than the developers ever did. — Supper (2025-04-21 13:31:54)

column5:
メモリーが　たりません\n
[call19]<$30><$BE>
column10:
note that you can erase multiple files through this interface -- even if you choose to erase one, the game will cycle through all the remaining ones and prompt you to erase them too, hence the need for plural "files" here. and to avoid making people think choosing "yes" will erase [i]all[/i] your data, better rephrase the message a bit. — Supper (2025-04-21 13:37:32)
actually, I'm not sure quite what the logic is. deleting the first of three files results in an immediate save, but deleting the second (of equal size) results in further prompts. maybe it's bugged, or the game's just really bad at defragmenting. — Supper (2025-04-21 13:43:33)
